__Algorithm__
```                                                         upvote if helpful```
- Gray code => a sequence of numbers where binary representation of any 2 consecutive numbers differ by exactly one bit
- For exaple for n = 1 => [ 0 , 1 ]
                          n = 2 => [00 , 01 , 11 , 10]
- To solve this we can understand to find gray code of n bits we need the gray code of n-1 bits and then add 0 and 1 at the front of those numbers
- for n = 2 we first find gray code for n = 1 which is [0 , 1] now we add 0 and 1 at the front of all elements in vectro 00 , 01 , 10 , 11 but here there is a discontinuity in 01 and 10 as to bits change
- so to resolve this we will add 0 to all integers in the order in which elements are there is vector and for adding 1 we will go in reverse order and push them accordingly . Like -> after adding o in front array will be 00 , 01 after adding 1 array will be 00 , 01 ,11 , 10 as for adding 1 in front the last element ie 1 is used and we go in reverse order
- During implementation we don't add 0 as the binary representation already consists of 0 for adding 1 we use bitmask ie 1<<(n-1) as for n = 2 we need to add 1 to 2nd place ie shift 1 by 1 place 
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> grayCode(int n) {
        if(n == 1){
            vector<int> vec = {0,1};
            return vec;
        }
