solutions.content:
First, let's analyse these kind of results:

n = 1:
```
Gray code = [0,1]
```
n = 2:
```
Gray code = [0,1,3,2]
```
n = 3:
```
Gray code = [0,1,3,2,6,7,5,4]
```
n = 4
```
Gray code = [0,1,3,2,6,7,5,4,12,13,15,14,10,11,9,8]
```
What are the patterns here?
```
The last number of gray code of n is 2^(n-1). For example for gray code of n = 4, the last number is 2^3 = 8
```
and
```
The first half of gray code of n is the gray code of n - 1
```
and
```
The second half of gray code of n can be constructed from the first half as in the example below:
```
For example: With the pattern above, n = 3, assume that we somehow already have gray code of n = 2 How can we calculate the second half?
```
[0,1,3,2,A,B,C,4]
```
Turns out:
```
A = 2 + 4 = 6 (element of gray code 2 at position [3] plus the last element of gray cod 3)
B = 3 + 4 = 7 (element of gray code 2 at position [2] plus the last element of gray cod 3)
C = 1 + 4 = 5 (element of gray code 2 at position [1] plus the last element of gray cod 3)
```

So we implement like this:
* Declare an array with 2^n elements.
* Init it with the last number of all gray code from 1 to n
* Then calculate the right half for each gray code of n (from 1 to n)

Like this (with n = 4)
```
_____________________________________ (array with 2^4 elements)
0_1___2_______4_____________________8 (last number of all gray code from 1 to 4)
0,1,3,2_______4_____________________8 (calculate the right half of gray code 2)
0,1,3,2,6,7,5,4_____________________8 (calculate the right half of gray code 3)
0,1,3,2,6,7,5,4,12,13,15,14,10,11,9,8 (calculate the right half of gray code 4)
```

Code:
```
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> grayCode(int n) {
        int s = 1 << n;
        int[] result = new int[s];

		/* Init it with the last number of all gray code from 1 to n */
        int val = s >> 1;
        while (s > 0) {
            result[s - 1] = val;
            val >>= 1;
            s >>= 1;
        }

		/* Construct the right half for each n from 1 to n */
        for(int i = 4; i <= result.length; i <<= 1) {
            addMoreValues(result, i);
        }

        return arrayToList(result);
    }

    private List<Integer> arrayToList(int[] array) {
        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
        for(int i = 0; i < array.length; ++i) {
            result.add(array[i]);
        }

        return result;
    }

    private void addMoreValues(int[] result, int m) {
        int mid = m >> 1;
        int addValue = result[m - 1];
        for(int i = 0; mid + i < m - 1; ++i) {
            result[mid + i] = result[mid - i - 1] + addValue;
        }
    }
}
```

