solutions.content:
The idea is simple; for example, consider `n = 2`, we have `{00, 01, 11, 10}` in binary.
Notice that the first half of the array starts with `0` and the second half starts with `1`. If we remove all the first bit, the array we have is **symmetric**, in which the first half is `{0, 1}` - the solution to `n = 1`

Consider `n = 3`, we have the array `{0, 1, 3, 2, 6, 7, 5, 4}`, or `{000, 001, 011, 010, 110, 111, 101, 100}` in binary. You can notice the same pattern: if we remove all the first bit, the first half of the remaining array is `{00, 01, 11, 10}` - the solution to `n = 2`.

So we can build the array as follow: start with `{0}`, for each additional bit (`ith` bit) you copy each element `a[j]` in the array *backward*, and add a bit `1` in front of it - equivalent to `a[j] | (1 << i)` 
-
*Note: the `1<<i` part is `100...0` with `i` bits `0`, when you use the operator `| - OR`, it will put the bit `1` in front of an `i` bit number - `a[j]` in this case*

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> grayCode(int n) {
        vector<int> a = {0};
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) 
            for (int size = a.size(), j = size-1; j >= 0; --j)
                a.push_back(a[j] | (1 << i));
        return a;
    }
};
```

