**APPROACH 1 : Brute Force**

* If ```k>=n``` do ```k = k%n```
* Create a ```temp``` array of size ```k```.
* Store the last ```k``` elements in a temp array.
* Shift the rest of the elements each by 1 position to the right.
* Store the last ```k``` elements in the first ```k``` indices.

**Time Complexity :** O(n)

**Space Complexity :** O(k)

**APPROACH 2 : Rotate k times**

* Rotate all the elements by 1 position ```k``` times.

**Time Complexity :** O()

**Space Complexity :** O(1)

**Code :**
```
class Solution {
public:
	void rotateByOne(vector<int> &nums){
		int n = nums.size(), temp = nums[n-1];
		for(int i=n-1; i>0; i--){
			nums[i] = nums[i-1];
			nums[0] = temp;
		}
	}
    void rotate(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        for(int i=0; i<k; i++) rotateByOne(nums);
    }
};
```

**APPROACH 3 : Reversal of array**

* Reverse the whole array.
* Then reverse the first k elements.
* Finally reverse the remaining elements.
(Do a dry run, it's very easy to understand)

**Time Complexity :** O(n)

**Space Complexity :** O(1)

**Code :**
