# Intuition
Suppose the question was to rotate right by one place,
eg: [1,2,3,4,5]  k=1
    then we would have:
   1. stored the last element in some temporary variable .
   2. shifted all the elements to the right-->nums[i]=nums[i-1].
   3. finally,put the temporary variable in the first index -->nums[0]=temp.

we will the same logic to solve this problem

# Approach
- observe carefully and try to compare the problem with the above one
- store the last 'k' elements in some temporary array
- now start shifting the 'n-k' elements to the end
- finally place the temporary array to the beginning 'k' positions.
- it might be confusing at first but trying doing it in pen and paper 




# Complexity
- Time complexity:
  This solution takes linear time complexity ->O(n)

- Space complexity:
  We are using an extra temp array , hence 
  space complexity ->O(n) , where n is the size of the array

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    void rotate(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
         int n=nums.size();
         k=k%n;

        vector<int>temp(k);

        int i=0;
        for(int j=n-k;j<n;j++){  
            temp[i]=nums[j];  
            i++;
        }

        i=n-1;  
        for(int j=n-k-1;j>=0;j--){
            nums[i]=nums[j];
            i--; 
        }

       for(int j=0;j<=i;j++){    
           nums[j]=temp[j];      

        }

    }
};

