solutions.content:
In this question we have been given an array and an integer .We to rotate k elements of the array.
In this approach a reverse function is created in which array , starting index and ending index is passed.Then using swapping technique we are reversing the array.

**Steps followed**

1 ). In the main function first we are reversing the whole array.
2 ). Then starting from 0th index till k-1 th index we will reverse the array.
3 ). In the last step starting from kth index till end index we are reversing the array.

Hence we will reach out to the output.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/588e3a64-320b-4311-9455-5685922ab470_1643525385.3704638.jpeg)

Here is the code

```
class Solution {
public:
    void reverse(vector<int>& nums,int start,int end){
        //creating a variable to stor one data
        int temp;
        while(start<end){   // traversing through the array

            //swappig first index with the last index
            temp = nums[start];
            nums[start]=nums[end];
            nums[end]=temp;

            //increasing starting index and decreasing ending index

            start++;
            end--;
        }
    }
    void rotate(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int n = nums.size();
        //if k is greater than size then making it in the range of size
        k=k%n;

        //if k is 0 or only one element in array no need to rotate
        if(k==0 || n==1)
        return;

        reverse(nums,0,n-1);    // reversing the whole array
        reverse(nums,0,k-1);    //reversing first half of array
        reverse(nums,k,n-1);    //reversing second half of array

    } 
};
```

This is a beginner friendly approach and easy to understand.

